  <h2>How does the certificate alert reach the response team?</h2>

  <p>
    The level 13 rule fires the moment FIM detects that a <code>.pfx</code>, <code>.p12</code>, <code>.cer</code> or <code>.key</code> file has been removed. Because Wazuh emails every alert at level 7 and above by default, a critical level 13 event is delivered immediately to the security mailbox, and the MITRE tag <code>T1485</code> lets your threat-hunting queries group it with other data-destruction activity. With <code>realtime="yes"</code> the notification typically arrives within seconds of the deletion, and the periodic 300-second baseline scan acts as a safety net in case a real-time event is ever missed. That combination is what turns "we think our certificates are protected" into auditable proof.
  </p>

